Last Blood Duel: MP3 Players vs Cell Phones
We will advise how to choose
While almost every cell phone can read MP3 files, no MP3 player can call.
This makes it clear that it is better to buy only the phone.
However, there are many reasons to get a self-published reader.
The choice depends entirely on the way of use and the needs of the future owner.
Perhaps you would hardly buy yourself an expensive high-quality turntable to listen to Maxim Turbulenc’s latest album.
First of all these music products do not come out as LP and from a qualitative point of view there is not even an objective reason.
But if your shelves are crowded with hard-rock, jazz or blues vinyls, you’ll probably dream of a turntable like that.
It also works with portable music, i.e. music compressed or simply in MP3 format.
Here too there are the price and quality categories.
For some it may be unacceptable to spend for a reader 8,000 crowns, just as a fan of Pink Floyd may hardly digest the headphones from twenty crowns in the market.
Two extremes between which there is enough space for everyone.
The choice is wide.
It is the life of the batteries that decides.
Some high-quality music players can do much more than just read music, but mobile phones don’t do it by mistake.
There is no other device as universal as the mobile phone.
Next to the primary functions, phone and text, it can read music and videos, record both and has a camera, sometimes better sometimes worse and maybe can even browse.
And if we take smartphones and handhelds into account, you will also have a miniature computer in your pocket.
It’s a little miracle because no refrigerator can grill and no television can photograph anything.
The universality of the mobile phone also brings disadvantages.
The more functions you use on the phone and the earlier the indicator on the screen will require the charger.
Reading music consumes a lot of energy.
Few phones can read music for more than twelve hours, usually, and much less.
In this sense, music players (especially the simplest ones) are much more effective.
As for cheap mobile phones, don’t count that they can last for more than a few hours.
If you still add us, from time to time, some calls , get to work for safety another charger, this also applies for the most expensive devices.
But you won’t have this problem with an MP3 player, even the worst ones last at least 9 hours at continuous functionality with one charge.
There is another problem when you download music to your cell phone.
Unfortunately, only a limited part of the devices has the universal USB port and not all of them can be connected to the computer without special software.
Of course the music can be recorded directly on the memory card, but only a few memory players are able to do it without an adapter for minicards that are not used in mobile phones.
Readers, with some exceptions (iPods) do not need any special software.
Simply fill the device with music via USB from your computer.
Most mobile phones and players create a media library on their own, sorted by the names of the performers, album name, genre, or user classification.
Some devices only reproduce the folder tree structure, similar to the Explorer tool in Windows, and some know how to do both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with operating system).
Readers are easier to handle, mobile phones can do more.
When choosing a particular device you are particularly interested in battery resistance, memory capacity, quality and type of audio outputs and clearly ease of use.
If the music is mainly for you as a background and if you listen to it every day just briefly on the tram you just have a cell phone that plays MP3.
That’s right now, of course, on any cell phone.
You don’t have to worry too much about which formats the phone or reader recognizes.
MP3 players support them all, the global majority of the music that comes to you will be in just this format.
In addition to this format that belongs to the most popular, the majority of devices support music in WMA format.
There is less AAC (format used by the company Apple and its iPods).
The best mobile phones also allow, for example, to buy music online.
Just visit, through the mobile internet, the corresponding pages of the operator (or another provider) and buy the song or album.
This same service could already be a valid argument for buying a mobile-reader.
Unfortunately, the offer of the operators is poor and is usually limited to hits of the moment of the radio.
The prices are not very low.
But it is generally assumed that this very way of selling music (whether via GSM, internet or wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people always carry their cell phones behind them.
Anyone who wants to listen to something squints in their pocket while the MP3 player stays forgotten at home.
But it also depends on this, if you always carry behind the headphones or at least the wireless headset.
If not, you can use the built-in player that almost every cell phone, but only a small part of MP3 players, has.
Perhaps the biggest benefit of mobile-readers will be, for many, the price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than 3,000 kronor.
For 3,000 and 4,000 crowns you will already buy a very dignified walkman.
Usually, however, you will be limited by the absence of an entrance for the common headphones.
The best and most technically equipped phones and also with the 3.5 mm socket for common headphones, cost up to 15,000 kronor.
But the advantage of readers is, besides others, easy handling.
The simplest ones aren’t necessarily the cheapest (see our choice) and anyone can really handle them.
The minimum of the functions, the similarity of the maneuverability once with the common stereo or perhaps the turntable, is obvious.
There is no danger of accidentally impacting the start of the mobile internet network and consequently of a giant bill for the transmission of data.
What device to take
Even the cheapest phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have an interchangeable memory card slot (such as M2, microSD, etc.).
Also with regard to the purchase of the respective card, you fall into the 2,000 crowns.
But be careful
Basic models only support cards with a maximum capacity of 2GB.
Only the most expensive ones can do it with 8 GB memory cards.
If you already have a mobile phone and also want to buy an inexpensive MP3 player, take Cowon, Creative, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB) you do not have to spend more than 1,100 crowns.
If you are one of the most demanding listeners, preferably take specialized mobile phones - walkman (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have individual keys for MP3 and the convenience of the service thus comes close to the same MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson has done more in this area, which have the same scale of use as MP3 players sold separately.
MP3 players of the above brands provide you with the same service and price category up to 4,000 crowns, but with a larger memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery resistance (usually 15 hours, generally up to 35 hours).
The first virtual operator will reach the Czech Republic as early as this year.
Maybe.
Perhaps the mobile phone market in the Czech Republic is quite mature and our operators offer virtually all the services as their partners in Western Europe.
However, there is something missing – a virtual trader that forces the traditional ones to lower the price.
Maybe it won't be missing for long.
Of the fact that Czech operators belong to the most expensive in Europe we have already written many times on Mobil.cz.
In the end, it was also confirmed by T, who pointed out that the price of SMS is higher in us than in the rest of the Union.
After the last steps by the European Commission in the field of regularising roaming charges, perhaps a paradoxical situation will be created - for some customers of Czech mobile operators SMS will cost less from abroad than at home.
How is it possible for prices in the Czech Republic to remain so high vis-à-vis Europe?
The answer is simple, it lacks the competition that would really like to start the confrontation.
Perhaps it sounds absurd, also here we have three mobile networks and coverage significantly above 100%.
Instead, mobile phone operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
The head of the Czech Telecommunication Council, Pavel Dvosak, has often stressed that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is perhaps true that the traditional operator with its own network no longer has many possibilities. (Moreover it may be difficult to find other frequencies by now).
But there is another possibility - the virtual operator.
Precisely the entry into the market of virtual operators has led to a considerable drop in prices, to which the traditional operators should have reacted.
At the same time before the entry of sharks like Tesko Mobile and Virgin Mobile into the market, similar rumors resounded in Britain as we do.
However, it has been proven that the place for such operators is there and that they can be really successful.
At the end of the day, we don’t have to go very far.
In February of this year we informed you of the arrival of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this operator has managed to win over 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest local operator.
At the same time, behind Mobilking is the financial group Penta, to which in the Czech Republic among other things U:fon belongs.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more concrete target group.
In order to work effectively, it takes a lot less customers than a traditional operator.
They do not carry behind, that is, relatively high expenses for the creation, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
So in the world virtual operators usually come at a low cost, offer calls and SMS at a low price, which is often in balance with the offer of the narrowest services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS that cost at least half as much as its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, even betting on a target group can be a pretty good move.
This operator focuses, so to speak, specifically on men.
“Real men choose Mobilking operator they like and can trust,” says David Seibertz, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, which produces this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept can be affirmed by us as in Poland.
Vodafone press spokesman Miroslav Epick: “The Czech market is relatively small for a fragmented approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition from the point of view of services is relatively saturated."
In the Czech Republic no possibility, say mobile network operators
But it seems almost certain that if there is ever a trader in the Czech Republic it will not be the Mobilking.
“We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not have a lot of expectations.
The ignition of Mobilking will instead take place in other countries in our area," Jana Studniková, the press spokesman for the financial group Penta, said in a telephone dialogue for Mobile.cz.
Thus he indirectly confirmed that the current operators in the Czech Republic are definitely not very supportive of this thought.
Rather, they try to do everything so that no potential competitor is created.
For some time now it has not hidden its interest in starting a virtual operator, the GTS Novera group that would like to take another step to become a real competitor of Telefonika O2 in the field of corporate customers.
“We have a great interest in being able to offer our customers not only fixed services but also mobile telecommunications.
And the sooner it is done the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all the Czech operators of the mobile network.
We have already made progress in negotiations with some of them,” said group spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
So maybe better times will come.
Unofficial information shows that the first virtual operator may have to have it by the end of the year.
But for now around his creation stands an impenetrable wall of silence.
“At the moment we do not believe that there is space in the Czech market for the creation of a full-fledged virtual operator.
The Czech market, unlike other markets, is very specific.
So far no one with a complex and serious project has addressed us," Vlastimil Sr?e?e? mentioned in his statement to Mobil.cz from the press section of Telefonika O2.
The specificity of the Czech market is also used by other operators.
T-Mobil press spokeswoman Martina Kemrová added in a rare deal with the O2 statement: “For now we have not noticed any commercial projects that are vital and beneficial for both of us, on which we can continue to build.”
He adds: “A virtual operator will hardly appear on the T-Mobil network by the end of the year.
At this point we would have had to have a concrete agreement on the table, so that it could be considered on the horizon.”
Vodafone focuses its attention rather on achieving its own 3G license requirements.
Miroslav ?epick? adds: “We are open to the negotiation of potential virtual operators, especially in the area of cost-sharing and infrastructure.
We consider this, from the point of view of customers, the most productive.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a common network for fast mobile internet.”
Competent authorities -with accomplices
The attitude of mobile operators can be easily understood, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would lead to lower prices and thus to a decrease in profit.
So why facilitate the rise of such a competitor?
The annoyances around the creation of U:fon testify that when operators care about something they can row on the same side.
Perhaps the great pressure was pressing against T in the period of the creation of U:fon towards the company of T-Mobile.
This testifies to the information of public access from the web pages of T.
But right now U:fon serves as the argument for which to not accept the virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová commented: “The competition environment in the mobile market has been greatly enhanced with the entry of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
Regarding the type of mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that the entry of another competitor would place on him and especially on his high-demand services.
The attitude of the mobile operators, however, is quite surprising the complete disinterest on the part of the Czech regulators.
It’s not just about the attitude of the “T” that unfortunately in the Czech Republic – unlike Britain and other developed countries – has no competence to interfere in economic competition.
This belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (OHS).
This, however, has taken on its typical position.
The entry of the virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible after the conclusion of the contract for the rental of the necessary infrastructure between the mobile operator and the virtual operator.
No such contract has been concluded so far because the offer from potential buyers has probably not been interesting enough for traditional operators,” Kristián Chalupa of the External Relations section of ?OHS said in a response to our question.
Such a formulated statement by the representatives of the operators is perhaps not surprising.
Instead, the office has to defend the interests of consumers and, moreover, take care of the fact that no one takes advantage of its position in the market, it is more than a delicate business.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "Overseas where virtual operators commonly work, we can see that their entry into the market has contributed to lower prices for mobile services."
But of course the pressure on the proper functioning of the market environment and the lowering of prices do not belong to the interests of OHS.
Truly shocking in the whole situation is the almost exciting harmony of these three operators resulting from their reactions.
The question of whether it is really just a coincidence arises on its own.
Just as the identical price of petrol for all petrol stations is the result of coincidence and competitive struggle.
“The section found no signs of anti-competitive behavior about this fact and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
No trader has a dominant position, so it has no corresponding greater responsibility for its behavior in the market.
The necessary tools for opening up the mobile network market for virtual operators may also be lacking to the telecommunications regulator,” Chalupa said in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of the many points of contention.
Of course, there is the relevant market analysis developed by T, according to which telecommunications are the only market from the point of view of economic competition.
In such a market, of course, no Czech trader has a dominant position.
But some legal experts offer another approach - for the creation of a virtual operator it is always necessary the agreement of the network operator.
And the mobile operator has – after all, logically – the monopoly of its network.
So for a certain portion it must be dominant by force.
But even if we don’t admit this argument, for OHS it should be a minimum warning for three mobile operators to proceed in such a strangely similar way.
At the same time, complaints from interested parties (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) show that during negotiations with all traders they encounter very similar obstacles.
Downloading responsibility to you in telecommunications is a fairly frequent trick with which you keep OHS out of the business.
We have already seen this in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, it was not possible to promote the expansion of the rights of T on the field of economic competition in telecommunications until the recent update of the telecommunications law, despite the fact that many experts expected the situation to improve.
This fact the representatives of OHS must know more than well, but perhaps their interests lie elsewhere.
It can be done when no one is watching.
But without us noticing it, the functioning of these pseudo-virtual operators remains, of which there are even some in Czech mobile networks.
These are companies that publish their own prices for mobile phone services, but they are only partially public.
These are usually the companies that deal with multi-level marketing.
So for example Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and a number of others offer their own mobile phone services.
The price lists of these companies usually reach only the pre-established people.
The magic lies in the fact that the company against the operator appears as a classic corporate customer, who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As a major customer you then receive special price offers (and more).
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit a similar presale.
“If the cases you are talking about arise, which we will be interested in, it could be a violation of the contractual conditions, and it could lead to the conclusion of the cooperation with that company,” Martina Kemrová replied to the question in question.
But it is quite unlikely that such an activity would reach the ears of those responsible for mobile operators.
Especially in the cases of the 3 companies mentioned it can be thousands of customers.
No operator at the same time defends itself against such an attitude.
From the activity of these companies they derive a not indifferent profit and at the same time - unlike real virtual operators - they are not damaged in any way with their own official marketing.
Miroslav ?epick? warns of possible problems: "The law allows for similar speculation, however only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
They must also accept that the SIM card in their phone is not registered on their behalf, so they cannot fully dispose of it as the regular customers of mobile operators.”
But that should be a little strange to you.
Then there is another question for OHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes to such an attitude, why do they block the creation of the virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that OHS has strong enough rights to expose similar activities and if it does not want to, it will not have to be satisfied with the explanation of the operators who have no idea of everything and that their trading conditions prohibit it.
When we are no longer expensive
As has already been said several times in the text, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile phone market has led to a considerable lowering of prices for services.
At the same time, in virtually every country where operators were born, traditional operators tried more or less to prevent their creation.
The arguments they used were practically identical - market too small, at the edge too saturated, problems with the quality of services etc.
In developed countries, however, regulatory bodies have intervened in these cases, not for mobile operators but for their customers.
Both with the formal measurements and with the non-formal pressure, then came the creation of the first virtual operator and he was joined by others.
Unfortunately, Czech regulators throw themselves from one to the other all the time like a boiling potato.
In our experience, we cannot get rid of the feeling that the lack of clarity of skills in these cases makes him more than comfortable.
But let's not toss the sponge.
If the backstage information is right and the virtual operator will really appear from us soon, the Czech mobile market will get back on its feet.
If one of the operators had consented to the creation of a virtual mobile operator, only OHS could hardly remain impassive to the rejection (discrimination) of the others concerned.
And perhaps we will stop calling at higher prices than the rest of Europe.
