1. Rats also have feelings
A rat or a cockroach run away when they feel danger.
The neuroscientist Joseph Le Doux is convinced: many animals also have feelings.
4. But how could we find out if, when they behave in the same way as we do, they have the same feelings as we do?
Articles by well-known scientists have been published in the Internet newspaper "Edge" for some years.
6. SPIEGEL ONLINE in a series presents chosen answers to the question: "What do you think is true, without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have feelings or other states of consciousness, without me or anyone else so far being able to prove it, since we cannot even prove that other men have consciousness.
But in this case we must at least hope that all human brains have the same basic configuration.
9. As soon as we address other species and ask questions about feeling or consciousness in general, we enter impractical territory, because the baseline does not match.
When a rat is in a dangerous situation, it does the same things that other animals do. That is, it pretends to be dead, flees or attacks.
People behave in a similar way, from which some scientists understand that there is a comparable subjective feeling.
I can't believe this.
Two aspects of the structure of the brain make it difficult for us to transmit our feelings to animals.
On the one hand, the lateral prefrontal cortex is often connected with human awareness, the associated circuits (this for its direct sharing of short memory and executive and control functions).
In man this large area is much more developed than in other primates and it seems that among other creatures it is completely missing.
At least in those aspects of our consciousness dependent on the prefrontal cortex, including knowledge, who we are, and the ability to plan and decide, we thus admit the foundation on the assumption that man differs even from other primates.
Another dramatic peculiarity should be presented in the way man speaks: since a large part of life is related to language, it is often said to be related to conscience.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
Although awareness does not depend on the language, it would influence it so that the animal’s awareness, as it is done, will certainly differ greatly from the circumstances of our consciousness.
This is why it is difficult to see how consciousness can be seen in other animals.
If it is not possible to measure it as an internal and subjective thing, in analyzing it through one’s own experience because of the special hardware, their research will pose us great problems.
Most interpretations refer to the content of conscious experience, but apart from this there is another aspect of consciousness to which science would be easier to access.
We could analyze the processes of animal consciousness without regard to their contents, and this is precisely the case in studies on the brief memory of primates, especially the example of visualization.
So for this principle, which Christof Koch and Francis Crick follow, we move on to the neural correlates of consciousness rather than the causal mechanisms: both could be identical but not necessarily.
Interestingly, this principle also highlights the value of the prefrontal cortex for the implementation of visualization.
So what does it mean for feelings?
I attribute them to the fact that an emotional system like that of fear is activated in one of its conscious brain activities.
What we refer to as “fear” is therefore the state of mind in which we find ourselves when the activity of the localized defense system in the brain (or its consequences, such as the body’s reactions) occupies the working memory.
In this way, feelings are closely related to the regions of the cortex, which characterize primates and in particular the human being.
With speaking nature, subtle nuances of feeling are created, because we can distinguish and categorize situations with the help of words and grammar, to describe them to others.
Antonio Damasio, for example, believes that feelings result from more primitive activity of the body regions of the sensations of the cortex and the cephalus paleo, similar to Jack Pankseep, who has nevertheless focused more on the cephalus.
Since this network over the course of human evolution has not changed much, this could absolutely be part of the feelings extended to the species.
On a purely theoretical level I cannot contradict it, however I find it indemonstrable.
Pankseep argues that what appears to rats and humans as fear probably feels that way to the senses in both cases: but how could it be verified, if rats and humans feel the same thing when they behave similarly?
Does a cockroach in case of danger run away as if he too felt fear?
In my eyes the mere resemblance of behavior cannot yet demonstrate any vital resemblance.
That is, the neural comparison continues to help: rats and humans have similar paleoencephalus, cockroaches not even a brain.
But is the paleoencephalus responsible for feelings?
And even if it could be proved to humans: how would you want to prove it to rats?
I think rats and other mammals, maybe even insects (who knows?), have feelings.
But I didn't know how to prove it.
And since their feelings are fundamentally different from ours (since human consciousness is based on specific circuits and language), I prefer to study the emotional behavior rather than the emotional sensations of rats.
In any case, here is progress at the neural level, as long as you renounce the same procedure on rats and men.
Just as I don’t do research on language and consciousness in rats, so I don’t do research on their emotions, I don’t even know if they exist.
This may be considered shortsighted, but I prefer to take steps forward, rather than continually bump into a wall.
I am an emotional practitioner.
