Truly attracting Hispanic voters is a complicated business.
Barack Obama’s educational projects are a significant example.
Mr. Obama’s campaign notes that, “African American and Latino students are significantly less likely to graduate than white students,” which is true.
To combat these shortcomings in achieving the goals, Obama’s educational plan specifically supports, among other things, “temporary bilingual education” for English students.
Yet the question for Obama is whether his commitment to bilingual education, which emphasizes teaching in classes of languages other than English, ignores his interest in bridging the learning gaps.
Take, for example, Sixth Street Prep, an elementary school in eastern Los Angeles County.
The school’s students are mostly Hispanic and low-income.
More than a third of students, many of whom have recently arrived, are studying English.
But, among fourth graders, an astonishing 100 percent of students took the upper-level test in the 2008 state math exam.
Equally astonishing 93 percent of fourth graders took the expert level test on art-of-language-English.
This incredible result was achieved using a different ingredient than Mr. Obama’s favorite.
Sixth Street emphasizes review and exercise, constant assessment of skills and an “no excuse” attitude.
Moreover, and this is where Mr. Obama should take note, according to Linda Mikels, director of Sixth Street, the school’s obstructive approach to English students is “full immersion.”
The use of English emphasizes the almost exclusive use of English in the context of education.
Ms. Mikels, who opposes bilingual education, told me, “We had a fantastic success with a freshman student from Mexico and if you were in class 12 months later you wouldn’t have been able to figure out which one it was.”
"It works," he noted, "for us it works."
Would Obama model a school like Sixth Street Prep to replicate it in other Hispanic-majority schools and with English students?
The school’s achievements make the answer to that question very easy, but education policy in its own party (the National Education Associations is a long-time supporter of bilingual education) and its own continued support for bilingual education prevents it from predicting Mr. Obama’s answer.
While he agrees that immigrants should study English, Obama recently made the topic trivial when he said that people should stop worrying about “English-only” legislation.
