The exploit in the second quarter marks a team record.
After spending more time than anyone in the Jets uniform for the past eight and more seasons, defender Shaun Ellis thought he had seen it all.
Then he watched the second quarter play out on Sunday, when the Jets turned a pointless game into a comeback.
"I've never seen such a thing," Ellis said.
The second quarter began after the Jets and the Arizona Cardinals had matched the grayness of the menacing clouds that overshadowed them with a flaccid game.
Then quarterback Brett Favre found Laveranues Coles for a 12-yard touchdown, providing the perfect signal for an afternoon where their growing tuning took a giant step forward.
Favre found Coles for two more touchdowns in the fourth, including one when a cornerback fell and another with 10 seconds left at the end of the first half.
“I didn’t get off my path,” Favre said of all the passages that came to Coles.
He's a great player.
Our communication has been great, despite what people may think.”
While Favre and Coles were playing catch games, the defense hit Cardinals quarterback Kurt Warner hard.
Cornerback Darrelle Revis intercepted a loose throw and relaunched it for 32 yards in a touchdown.
Security Eric Smith planned another pass and intercepted it.
Linebacker David Bowens makes a Warner fumble.
The last turnover, the forced fumble by Bowens, may have been the most remarkable.
The Cardinals were ahead on that ball possession, with 10 seconds left, and after the Jets had picked up the ball with 10 minutes left, Jay Feely kicked a 20-yard goal, for a 34-to-0 lead.
It was more than the Jets ever scored in a quarter.
When asked to describe the madness, Jets coach Eric Mangini said, "The second quarter or the third quarter?"
When both were told – the Jets gave 21 unanswered points in the third quarter – Mangini said: “I can tell you that I liked the second quarter a lot more than the third.”
There were a lot of points in a small amount of time.”
Rested Gebrselassie surpasses his world record
Haile Gebrselassie of Ethiopia showed again why many consider him the best marathoner ever, breaking his own world record at the Berlin marathon on Sunday and becoming the first person to run a 26.2-mile race under the 2 hours and 4 minutes.
With a win on the favorably flat run in 2:03:59, Gebrselassie shattered his previous score of 2:03:26 last year in Berlin for 27 seconds.
At 35, Gebrselassie sets the 26th world record for such an astonishing career that he has produced a world championship or world record at every distance from the metric mile to the marathon.
Last month, Gebrselassie skipped the Beijing Olympic marathon, fearing - perhaps too alarmingly, in retrospect - that air pollution would make his asthma problems worse.
Instead, he decided to run to Berlin.
In almost perfect conditions - sunny and 48 degrees on departure, 55 degrees on arrival - Gebrselassie won Sunday with a scorching average of 4 minutes and 43 seconds per mile.
As soon as half-tourists such as Gebrselassie and Paul Tergat of Kenya went to long distances, the marathon record fell by more than two minutes in the past decades, since Ronaldo from the Brazilian Coast won in Berlin in 2:06:05 in 1998.
After Sunday’s victory, Gebrselassie told reporters that two weeks ago he had calf cramps and missed a week of training.
Clearly, the rest left him fresh, not rusty.
“I’m so happy,” Gebrselassie told reporters.
"Everything was perfect.
I started again a week ago, and I had some doubts today, but in the end everything went well.”
He has been somewhat criticized – especially in Kenya, Ethiopia’s East African rival – for overly orchestrating his races, generally avoiding many of the world’s best marathon stars, relying on track openers as if it were a mid-bottom race, and putting world records above the sense of competition.
But these criticisms rarely diminish Gebrselassie’s proficiency as a marathoner.
With the pace paced by four Kenyans on Sunday, Gebrselassie reached the halfway point in 1:02:04.
Two elite Kenyan runners, James Kwambai and Charles Kamathi, held Gebrselassie in competition after the track openers vanished.
Just over three miles from the finish, Gebrselassie made a final climb to separate from Kwambai, who finished second in 2:05:36, improving his personal best time by almost 5 minutes.
Kamathi came third in 2:07:48.
In the women’s race, Irina Mikitenko, a native of Kazakhstan who is now a German citizen, completed a remarkable year by winning in 2:19:19, the seventh fastest time ever.
Paula Radcliffe of Great Britain holds the world record of 2:15:25.
Last spring, Mikitenko, 36, was a surprise winner of the London Marathon in 2:24:14.
She missed the Beijing Games with what is described as a bad accident, but she healed to win in Berlin, making her best personal time of nearly five minutes in the third marathon she ran.
She ran a race doing the calculations well, letting a quartet of Ethiopian and Kenyan runners leave with a large detachment, picking them up after about 18 and a half miles.
Askale Tafa Magarsa of Ethiopia came second in 2:21.31, while Helena Kiprop of Kenya finished third in 2:25:01.
In a city apart, pride and processes of a black life
Hidden in the theme park extended on the outskirts of Orlando, a few miles from the splendor, the noise, the huge, lies the quiet city where the pride and complications of the African-American experience come into life.
Eatonville, the first all-black city incorporated into the country and the birthplace of Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer as simple as he described it in 1935: "the city of five lakes, three croquet fields, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, plenty of guava, two schools and no prison."
It is now a place of pilgrimage.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee came to the annual Zora! Festival in Eatonville to show their respect for Hurston, the most famous writer of Harlem Renaissance.
Yet in many ways, the city it has described – and makes tourists stop by including it in Florida’s tour guide produced by the Depression-era Federal Writers’ Project – remains a place apart.
It’s as independent, dignified, and private as it was in the 1930s, when Hurston wrote that rural blacks in Florida often resisted sharing their thoughts with the white man, that “knowing so little about us, he doesn’t know what he’s missing.”
Even now, in a year where a black nominee for president, Senator Barack Obama, was called in for an opening speech on race, many here remain wary of the outsider’s gaze.
“We are very cautious about how our story is told,” said Hortense Jones, 59, a lifelong resident and a member of the city’s oldest church.
"It must be right."
Eatonville has long been defined as a paradox of triumph and difficulty.
It is both a historical model of black power grab and a community of nearly 2,400 where the poverty rate is twice the national average.
It is a literary center but also an example in the shade of the oaks of southern black rural culture - sometimes despised, sometimes awarded - born of American slavery.
Not surprisingly, the residents here are both proud and protective.
And the preoccupation with the image of Eatonville really began with Zora, who everyone here calls Hurston.
She introduced the world to her hometown through candid, dialect-rich books such as "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937).
Five Florida guide paragraphs transformed the city, just outside Route 17, a road that runs through the often-forgotten center of Florida within a scenario of black history and human drama.
Low on both life and literature, Hurston took readers to the store owned by Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then diverted to more private areas.
“Away from the left,” he wrote, “is the modern public school, brown with white finishes, with its well-maintained gardens and courtyards, which Howard Miller always looked after, thinking he could just read and write.”
She also mentioned widow Dash's new husband and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of all kinds and whatever fits the passage rooms."
So in just a few hundred words, Hurston connected Eatonville with self-government but also with illiteracy, second marriage and sex.
Clearly this was not Fodor's.
In fact, it was not a portrait that everyone appreciated.
“Zora was saying it as it was,” said Ella Dinkins, 90, one of Johnson’s girls whom Hurston immortalizes by quoting men singing gross songs about their beauty.
He adds: "Some people don't like it."
Hurston is still remembered here as a lively eccentric who frequently returned from her family moved to Jacksonville, Fla.
Augustus Franklin, 77, remembers that when Hurston plummeted into the city, he usually arrived without warning in a triumphant Chevrolt, smoking and wearing pants in a city that even today boasts of decent clothing.
Many inhabitants were fascinated, says Mr. Franklin, while others whispered.
“People were always very happy to see Zora,” Mr. Franklin said.
But, he added, swinging in his chair on the back patio above Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, "she never stayed long."
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books had gone out of print.
Along with the rest of the world, Eatonville seemed to have forgotten her.
Although she was once a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an unmarked tomb in Fort Pierce, Fla., where she had lived.
In Eatonville, there were no great commemorative ceremonies, and no great conferences.
"I don't think they understand his contribution to the world or his legacy to everyone," said Valerie Boyd, author of "Wrapped in Rainbows," a 2003 biography of Hurston.
A change occurred in the 1980s.
Orange County officials wanted to place a five-lane highway across the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the two-lane main road.
Orlando’s expansion has already pushed Interstate 4 through the city’s western boundary.
The proposal came when Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult period in its history.
Forced integration, in addition to other things, had ended the relative idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950s, the battle over racial mixing brought hatred to the door of the community.
“During that time, a group of white boys came and threw oranges and things at the people sitting on one side,” says Mr. Franklin.
“We actually had a girl who was killed by that one once.
They threw a watermelon out of a car.”
In a 1955 letter to The Orlando Sentinel, Hurston made a request to the Supreme Court for forced integration, calling his decision in Brown against the school office "an insult rather than an honor to my race."
Residents now say that the desegregation of schools, despite being positive in some respects, dilutes the cohesion of Eatonville and jeopardizes the confidence of its young people.
"Black kids were used to being hugged - I remember this - hugging your teacher in the morning, hugging your teacher in the evening," said N.Y. Nathiri, the daughter of Ella Dinkins and the executive director of Preserve the Eatonville Community, a nonprofit group.
This lasted, he added, until teachers and students came from the same place.
"You weren't embracing your white teacher because your white teacher -- I mean, there's a cultural divide there," Mrs. Nathiri said.
Civil rights, however, helped and created space for many more Zora Neale Hurstons – black writer, actress, and artist who overcame prejudice, as she did, with cheerful self-confidence and lines like, “How can some deny themselves the pleasure of my company!
I just can't understand."
In 1975, writer Alice Walker began a long journey to Hurston’s unmarked grave and began to fight for the resurrection of her reputation.
Five years later, an acclaimed biography on Hurston by Robert E. Hemenway hit bookstore shelves, reintroducing it into the American canon.
The highway project came just as his most famous daughter had once again turned the limelight.
And this time, Hurston's old neighbors saw her as a savior.
The community began designing in 1988 a festival dedicated to Hurston to show what could ruin the state with its highway.
Thousands of fans came to the inaugural event two years later, and every January, many return for the commemoration.
Many years later, the state pulled back from its project on the street.
"The five lanes of the resuscitated highway brought what would be high speed, a real pride for the city," Ms. Nathiri said.
Mrs. Boyd puts it more simply: "Zora saved Eatonville."
Victory over the highway project helped change the image the city has of itself.
Outsiders like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who started coming to church here in 1993, began appearing in large numbers, and residents began reevaluating the past.
Eatonville was added to the public historical register in 1998.
A new one-storey bookstore (called Hurston, of course) opened in 2006 on a revamped and embellished Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville remains a Florida anomaly: just six miles from downtown Orlando, it can give the feeling of a side street in the summer rain, as small as when it was founded with just 27 black families in the 1980s.
(It’s 90 percent black today.)
Outsiders who come to search for the history of Eatonville, for its meaning, are often still treated with caution.
A permission requested in advance is required for most of the interviews, at some things - such as the murals on the oldest church in Eatonville, painted by a white man, which show black men in the fields - are not allowed to be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, such as Ms. Jones, a naughty teacher, with a soft spot for bright red, still fear that their island community will be misunderstood.
Yet as the Hurston festival expanded, a high level of city pride also emerged.
Young people, in particular, tend to see Eatonville with Hurston seeing her entire race: beautiful, trouble and everything, no better, no worse and fair, creative, great worker, silly and confused as other races and ethnic groups in America.
It is sincere civic affection what can be heard in the voice of Mr. Franklin’s grandson, Edwin Harvey, 18, who plans to return to Eatonville after college to work in the local government or for the Police Department, which he said may need help.
And even younger ones, like Alondra and Alexia Kenon, 11-year-old twins from Winter Park, seem to have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
“A lot of people, if they just got in here, will think, ‘Oh, this city is nothing compared to all the others,’” Kenon said after mass on a recent Sunday.
“But if you really stop and take a moment to look at history, it’s really a pretty city.”
Here in New York we all talk fluently about finance.
On the surface, nothing has changed.
If tourists in Manhattan were to stay away from the newspaper stalls and huge TV screens in Times Square, they wouldn’t notice being in the eye of the cyclone.
They would never guess that the glass offices, honeycomb over their heads, the bankers and hedge fund managers who monopolise New York live every day the worst “bad day in the office” since the collapse of 1929.
The stewards shake metal trolleys for tea across the sidewalks, carrying trays of muffins for breakfast meetings.
Latin Americans drag their feet between condominiums carrying, like human mules, 50 broken stretched shirts hanging on a stick on their shoulders.
Employees are still waiting in line for their morning bagels at the food carts on the sidewalks, and it is still impossible to take a yellow taxi between 4 and 7 p.m. on a working day.
It didn’t seem like there was a real crisis, until, with all the talk of ruin and sadness, I decided to open a new savings booklet on Thursday afternoon.
Although I had planned the matter so that it coincided with the late afternoon break at my JP Morgan Chase branch, a queue of about twenty was already waiting in line.
Not in front of the cashier’s desk, to collect money or make deposits, but in front of the customer service desk, where old customers order checkbooks, tourists ask for directions to the Macy department store and new customers open accounts.
Many of those in front of me, I would have learned from Starr, my “trusted banker,” were in line for my own reason.
Unlike me, however, they have already taken savings from smaller banks from places where they commute, such as those from New Jersey, Pennsylvania, and Staten Island.
They took the money from the so-called thrifts (a bit like a construction company), credit unions and types of city savings banks whose branches operate only within a state, and they say they treat customers like family members.
In recent years, 15 of these banks have gone bankrupt.
In recent days, Washington Mutual, a bank with $327 billion in assets, has been submitted to controlled administration, and as New Yorkers headed home for the weekend on a Friday afternoon, another bank, Wachovia, with $440 billion in savings deposits, was looking for a buyer to save it.
The employees and clerks in front of me, frightened by another collapse, were moving their money to a bank perceived as a safe haven, the bank that is asking for more bail on Wall Street.
Common New Yorkers in recent weeks have become proficient in finance.
A woman at my trusted Chinese supermarket, speaking on the phone, referred to Lehman Brothers, the bank that went bankrupt, and her emaciated CEO Dick Fuld in all familiarity, as if complaining about a lazy colleague.
And Lyn, the uniformed concierge, almost fifty of my condo, changed the theme compared to our normal topic of conversation about Brad and Angelina or the delivery of my groceries.
She told me, after my visit to the bank, “Now I have all my savings in market funds!.
I’ve changed, I’m not taking any risks.”
Muslim tombs desecrated while Austria turns to the right.
Heinz-Christian Strache, left of the Austrian right wing of the Freedom Party and Filip Dewinter of the Belgian right-wing party Vlaams Belang, take part in a demonstration to present the organization "City against Islamization" in Antwerp, Thursday, January 17, 2008.
They carry road signs representing mosques with a red line passing in between.
Police blamed right-wing extremists for desecrating a Muslim cemetery in Austria, the same week that far-right political parties gained a lot in the national general election.
More than 90 graves were severely damaged at the Traun cemetery near Linz, sometime between Friday night and this morning, in what police believe was an organized action.
The culprits sprayed Jewish symbols like the Star of David over some graves, but the detectives believe it may have been an attempt to disguise extremist motivations driven by a hatred for Muslim immigrants.
It is unclear whether the incident is related in any way to the election.
A spokesman for the local Islamic community said they were "deeply shocked" by the news of the desecration, which took place towards the end of Ramadan, a month of religious significance for Muslims.
Austria, meanwhile, has embarked on a journey of spiritual research following its right-wing turn in yesterday’s parliamentary election.
The two far-right parties that took nearly 30 percent of the vote, the Austrian Freedom Party and the Alliance for the Future of Austria, campaigned with vehemently anti-immigration tickets and some of their slogans were defined by xenophobic critics.
Heinz-Christian Strache, the leader of the Freedom Party who won more than 18 percent of the vote, campaigned against veils and burqas and also voiced his opposition to foods that are perceived to be connected to Islam.
At the final meeting in Vienna, he spoke of a “European brotherhood” to prevent the growth of Islam.
Both parties appear to ban the construction of mosques and minarets, arguing that they are political symbols of continued Islamization of Austria and Europe.
Polls and analyses made immediately after the election, which established the far right as the nation’s strongest political bloc, indicating that the change was brought about predominantly by young voters who are concerned about their future in the European Union.
Travelling abroad is forbidden to Gary Glitter.
Gary Glitter, the glamorous rock star guilty of child sexual abuse, has been banned from traveling to France and Spain from court.
The magistrates imposed a six-month ban on Glitter after he had informed the authorities that he wanted to go to Spain via France.
The ban on travel abroad was granted to Kent police last Thursday after they provided magistrates with evidence of Glitter's previous arrests for sexual abuse of minors.
Glitter, real name Paul Gadi, was not present at the hearing at the Ashford prefecture in Kent but was represented by Corker Binning's lawyers.
A spokesman for the Court Service said: "On Thursday, September 25, at Ashford Prefecture, Kent police filed a request to prevent Mr. Paul Gadd's trip abroad to France and Spain until March 25.
"Paul Gadd was not present in person."
Glitter, 64, had informed authorities that he wanted to travel abroad as required by the sex offender registry.
He must inform the authorities if he wishes to travel abroad for more than three days.
He is also asked to give the police seven days notice of his scheduled departure date.
Failure to notify the authority can lead to a sentence of five years in prison.
Kent police said they did not want to discuss individual cases or possible Glitter moves in the country.
A Kent police spokesman said: “Kent police will do everything necessary to protect children in this country or abroad.
“From our point of view, it’s easier to control someone who stays in the UK because we have suitable comprehensive systems to manage any potential risk more effectively.
“Protecting Kent residents is the main concern of the Kent police and we work closely to monitor the behavior of convicted sex offenders registered in the country to minimize any possible risk to the public.
Glitter returned to the UK last month after spending 27 months in a Vietnamese prison for abusing two 10- and 11-year-old girls.
When Glitter arrived he flew to Bangkok where he was to board a flight to London.
But he said he felt sick and refused to fly to London.
Thai authorities would not have passed him to passport control and he eventually took a flight to Hong Kong.
The Chinese authorities also refused to let him in and he returned to Bangkok where Thai police and immigration officials insisted he return to England.
He eventually arrived at Heathrow Terminal 3 on 22 August and stayed there while his lawyer David Corker went to the Uxbridge prefecture, west of London, since Scotland Yard had successfully applied for an order to place him in the sex offender registry.
Glitter was previously incarcerated in the UK in 1999 for possessing images of child abuse.
A source at the interior ministry said Jacqui Smith, the secretary of the interior, felt reassured and happy that Glitter had been stopped from traveling to France and Spain.
"I photograph the master away from the scene to extract his character" Günther Bauer, photographer
No heels, no steering wheels, no clothes from before.
Only the essence of the great masters of flamenco, stripped of the concentration that characterizes the interpretation, to look at the relaxed appearance of man or woman.
On the one hand, the artist.
On the other hand, the person.
Two inseparable faces, except in the private, in those moments away from the public, when the intimacy of a gesture, the depth of a stolen look or the expressiveness of the hands, are natural because they do not have to go on stage.
The German Günther Bauer in "Flamenco-People" alternates the theatricality of some shots to singers, dancers and guitarists on stage with the lesser known side of these masters.
With this objective, the photographer offers an original iconography of flamenco, grasping it from different visual angles.
The exhibition, included in the program of the Flamenco Photography Month, reflects the international importance of this dance, which is growing every day,” explains the artist and clarifies that in “Flamenco-People” they could also be ordinary people, but seeing the photos, the observer realizes that they are not the typical images of artists, performers or performers on the scene.
These people portrayed “on the street” are “artists capable of conveying passion, sadness, joy when they are on stage ... and capturing the audience.
In order to capture the personality of these greats it is not necessary to portray them on stage,
because their personality and character are interior.
What interested me was to create an intimate atmosphere that would allow me to capture with the camera the personality of the greats of flamenco.”
With a passion for the "Cante de las Minas" festival, Bauer began in 1997 a long journey aimed at portraying singers, guitarists or dancers using a plate camera.
They are portraits that, due to the type of machine and the material, resemble classical photography.
The application of different stylistic techniques breaks with the traditional principles of the image, giving the photo modernity, according to an idea that reflects Bauer's own flamenco conception: "A music with very traditional roots that evolves and is able to surprise every day."
Not dancing, singing or playing itself, but the personality of the artist, his character, capable of conquering the audience with his art.
The search for an encounter with the essential elements, with magic that becomes visible in a certain way of feeling and being, are and have been the constant of this work, on display these days at the gallery El Fotómata.
Famous flamenco artists such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, are included in this selection of about seventy portrait artists.
The project has become a sort of flamenco anthology, and will soon be published in a book that will collect the portraits exhibited at the exhibition.
The passion for portraiture led Bauer to repeat the idea two years ago with "Portraits of Veteran Athletes" ("SportARTproject").
Although in "Flamenco-People" the concept is different, the photographer admits "I love portraying people, getting to know them and being able to penetrate for a moment in their lives, whether this is a long or a short moment.
I think portraiture is the hardest genre in photography.
You meet or compare with people, characters you sometimes don’t even know or who only give you a few minutes to take the picture.
Beyond these circumstances, like a photographer, I always try to put my ideas into practice.”
The collection of portraits of contemporary flamenco, entitled "Flamenco-people" is set up at the El Fotómata gallery, at number 20 via de la Mata, parallel to via Alameda de Hercules, and will be open to the public until next 16 October.
