Talking in Sleep
Some children talk at night.
I do not mean those who wake up very agitated to tell us something that happened to them the day before, but those children who talk while staying asleep.
The first time it happens, at best it takes a scare, but it doesn’t really matter much.
This is a benign sleep disorder called sleep disorder.
It manifests itself with a certain frequency, especially in children and adolescents.
Surely, most of you have been told that you had spoken in your sleep.
This phenomenon can occur very sporadically (once in a lifetime, for example associated with an episode of high fever) or with greater regularity (every day, once a week, once a month ...), the day after the child remembers nothing.
There is no single reason for this phenomenon.
Sometimes they are episodes related to other sleep disorders such as nightmares, nighttime fears, nighttime enuresis (pissing in bed), or sleepwalking, but this is not necessarily the case.
As mentioned above, it can be associated with very high fever stages, stressful situations or overexcitement.
In any case, it is a phenomenon still little studied.
The intensity with which it appears is also extremely variable.
It can happen that the person speaks in a very quiet tone of voice, with loose words, almost in a whisper or that the opposite happens (crying, screaming, long speeches ...).
In cases where the event is particularly intense, it would be advisable to observe the child and possibly consult a specialist to check if there is any issue that is generating an abnormal state of anxiety as an outlet for the situation.
We have said that this is a benign alteration so there is no treatment unless it is associated with other sleep disorders that can be treated (for example, if paired with insomnia or stressful situation).
What you can do, however, is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to overexcite your baby before he goes to sleep.
Propose quiet games and avoid programs or TV shows that incite fear or suggest violence.
With very nervous children for whom it is difficult to relax, relaxation techniques can be used to help them acquire some inner calm.
This will allow the child to sleep more peacefully.
Once the sleepwalkers appear try to keep calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will not remember anything that happened.
Useful advice
Don't wake him up.
It is useless, because he is not aware of what is happening, and you would interrupt his sleep.
Although he’s talking, he’s sleeping and so he’s resting.
Remember that if you appear very distressed and episodes have a certain frequency it is better to consult a doctor or check where such great anxiety comes from in the child.
If you understand what he says (which isn’t the most common situation), don’t fall into the temptation to interview him for information.
You will get nothing because he is asleep and therefore not conscious to organize his thinking.
In addition, you are able to hear what he says but not see what he is dreaming of saying, so you need to pay close attention to the interpretation of the information and the conclusions it might lead to.
Never tell your child that you could ask him questions at night to learn his secrets.
Not even a joke.
Something like that causes a huge anguish.
In short, don’t worry, it’s nothing serious, it’s an episode that only lasts a few minutes.
