The blood is safe again.
Héma-Québec celebrated its tenth anniversary yesterday, and its president, Dr. FrancineDécary, had every reason to rejoice, as Héma-Québec has become one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
And most importantly, it regained the public’s trust, seriously shaken by the blood-infected scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As we know, the national blood supply managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service was infected with acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C in the 1980s.
Faced with such a tragedy and protests from the population, the Government of Canada conducted in February 1994 a public inquiry, led by Judge Horace Krever, which aimed to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to disseminate recommendations to prevent the resumption of a similar disaster.
While Judge Krever was slow to draft a report, some provinces set up a committee with the aim of devising a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, this mandate was carried out by the Gélineau committee.
As a result of the Gélineau et Krever relations in Canada, two suppliers were created: Héma-Québec to supply Québec and the Société canadienne du sang (Canadian Blood Society) for all other provinces and two territories.
In 1998, when Héma-Québec started its activities, only 38 percent of people said they still had confidence in the donation system in Quebec, recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was mortifying.
Thanks to continued efforts to improve the safety of blood collections and field research over the following years, we have regained the public’s trust,” he explains, before proudly stating that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of Quebec’s population now had confidence in Héma-Québec.
However, Dr. Décary is convinced that “trust is something extremely fragile”.
Since its creation on September 28, 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At the time, there were numerous cases in Europe of the human variant of the mad cow, a new manifestation of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says her who has been the president since 1998, the year of the foundation.
"And we didn't know at all if that disease could be transmitted through infected blood.
This was based on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélinau reports, according to which when you have doubts and could get a serious disease, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease that manifests itself with a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, exclusion measures are taken.
In April 1999, the blood of those who had spent more than a month in the UK since 1980 was refused.
Now, for a few years, it has been proven that this disease is undoubtedly transmitted through infected blood.
This episode has shown us that it made sense to apply the precautionary principle.”
In 1999 a much more efficient technique for the detection of HIV appeared on the market: nucleic acid tests (TANs) that allow to directly recognize in the blood of donors the presence of the virus and not that of antibodies against it, on which the tests used until then were based.
TANs have allowed us to reduce the window period, that is, from the moment the person contracted the disease to the moment when the first viruses can be detected in the blood thanks to our techniques, explains the specialist.
This period could be reduced to less than a week.
The risk of ignoring the presence of infected donors and therefore not being able to detect them has thus greatly decreased.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS with a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people is at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
“In other words, this means you’ll need to distribute 12 million blood samples before someone gets infected with the HIV virus.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood samples each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmitted with a transfusion is found.
I believe that today you can feel comfortable receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover your health, says the head of management of Héma-Québec.
“Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen will emerge in the system.
A year ago, the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted into the blood by an insect.
You have to be constantly vigilant," continues Dr. Décary before pointing out that in addition to having secure resources, Héma-Québec must also provide enough.
“The needs increase as the population ages.
Being the most aggressive cancer treatments, patients often need an intake of red blood cells or platelets.
The aging of the population also has consequences on the number of donors, which on average constitutes only 3% of the inhabitants of Quebec acceptable as donors.
All healthy people who are 18 years old and meet the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who volunteer as donors are not accepted, because they are affected by AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled to a country where it is widespread, they will be refused for a period of one year.
“With this 3% we manage to maintain an inventory capable of meeting the needs of hospitals.
Cases of shortage are very rare.
But we must renew the members of this group of donors as they get older and can no longer make donations.
It is now difficult to convince people to donate blood, but above all to hold them back and incite them to become regular donors.
Nowadays life is so hectic that it’s hard to find an hour to donate blood,” says desolate Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec not only distributes blood samples, but also human tissues, including bone transplants, eyeball heart valves and skin that is used almost exclusively for severe burns.
These tissues are analysed, processed and frozen before being deposited at Héma-Québec, which runs the only public umbilical cord blood bank in Quebec.
In the umbilical cord, which was once considered a biomedical waste, there is plenty of stem cell-rich blood that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
“We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the bank entry of our thousandth cord blood sample and we plan to take more than a thousand each year.
They should start to be proposed for transplants early next year," says Dr. Décary, who describes the practice of cord blood collection as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed that they can't access them," because Héma-Québec doesn't have the means to propose this complex and expensive program in all Quebec hospitals.
