Free Opinion - Barrick Gold's Orwellian Speech
In the September 17 edition, Le Devoir published a letter from M. Patrick J. Garver, executive vice president of the Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
Pursuing Orwellian logic, the latter claims that the world’s largest gold company filed a six-million-dollar defamation lawsuit against three authors and a small, squatted publishing house with the intention of initiating a “transparent public debate.”
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth they judge, especially in the case of a defamation lawsuit, but the law.
Unsurprisingly, this substantial difference is completely hidden by Garver.
Because for Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate would be to ruin anyone who dares to hold a position contrary to hers.
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the writers and publisher of the book Canada Nero will have to spend a considerable amount of money in order to organize their defense and fight, with decidedly odd weapons, against an army of lawyers financed by the practically bottomless pockets of the mining company.
Moreover, in these unequal arms fights, the tactic is often to ruin the defendant in order to impose a consensual settlement that will overwhelm the opposition as well as frighten anyone who dares to pronounce again on the issue.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it is before the public that she should have presented her view of the facts.
Contrary to what happens in many countries where Barrick Gold works, in Canada the debates are usually held with the exchange of opinions and not at the whiplash.
It would have been enough for the company to open its books, its documents, and set up a real debate, through newspapers, media, publications, and funding from teams of independent researchers who could shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold doesn’t seem to have too much confidence in public opinion and wrongly rejects petitions and letters in support of Black Canada authors.
Perhaps Garver could explain how he can demand a "public debate" when his contempt for that same audience is clearly evident?
In the world of the vice-president, it seems that this word indicates only profusely paid lawyers and not the whole of Canadians; here is a rather narrow view of the concept.
In a democratic system, even denigrators have the right to speak.
What Barrack Gold doesn’t understand – or doesn’t want to understand – is that the public that supports the authors and publishers of Black Canada does so primarily because it rejects the brutal means adopted by the mining company.
This audience is ready to listen to Barrick and judge, but on the basis of civilized exchanges of opinion, and not from the perspective of what many perceive as a kind of embarrassment (in seeking the "public debate", Barrick Gold has just given the authors of Black Canada an ultimatum urging them to suspend the use of that word...)
Beyond Garver’s surreal discourse, the Barrack Gold lawsuit constitutes a direct attack on the freedom of university research and the pursuit of truth, indispensable in any democratic society.
It denies the right to cite authentic sources and to debate facts and interpretations, which represent the very basis of intellectual work.
If in a country like Canada it is impossible to study and argue about uncomfortable topics for the richest companies in the world, who will be able to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, she could do so by following scientific norms as the authors of Canada Nero do.
You have the right to reply.
For a long time, the university environment, of which we are a part, has been able to handle debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold’s excessive measures clearly show that, contrary to her claims, she is not seeking a transparent debate at all.
This is at the expense of the university world, as is the case with the public debate itself in Canada, and it is time for governments to adopt measures to limit abusive lawsuits.
