It provides in particular: checks on its effective implementation by elected leaders, new mechanisms to ensure the reimbursement of public money, new provisions to contain the number of houses seized for non-payment, as well as a right of inspection on the remuneration paid to the managers of the protected enterprises.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, House Speaker Nancy Pelosi and the Republican representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight yesterday at the end of a two-day negotiation marathon.
“We have made great progress toward an effective market deal,” said Bush administration Representative Henry Paulson.
“Every decision has been made in such a way as to safeguard the American economy and people from the ongoing crisis on Wall Street,” he said.
“It’s the crucial point: If we hadn’t acted in this way, invaluable discomfort and turmoil would have poured into the daily lives of Americans,” said U.S. Rep. Judd Gregg.
The conclusion of the negotiations was marked by concerns about the impact of a new bankruptcy on investors.
The time limit agreed corresponded to the opening of the markets this morning.
Joining later in the negotiation, the two candidates for the US presidency have been rather supportive of the agreement, while still expressing their dissatisfaction with the adoption of extreme solutions.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama is credited with adding some provisions to the agreement, particularly the one that will allow owners to maintain their domicile and that related to salaries for executives of companies covered by the state.
“When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of others, there is nothing to rejoice about.
But these measures are necessary,” he said on the American television screen.
Interviewed on another channel to find out if he will vote in favor of the plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, replied: "I would like to analyze the details, but I hope so."
“According to what I’ve read, it’s something that we all have to digest and that will allow us to move forward.”
The option of non-intervention is simply unacceptable,” he said.
The 700-billion-dollar plan aims to repurchase with taxpayer money the dubious, risky and unsold assets of American financial institutions.
The plan comes after 14 months of crisis due to the bursting of a housing bubble that led first to the collapse of at-risk (mutual) mortgage loans, then to extend to other more widespread forms of credit securities (PCAA) and lead to the freezing of liquidity and the upheaval of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of Republicans in charge who aired the first draft of a deal last week.
They seem to have come out of that dead end since the Democrats accepted that the “toxic” assets of some struggling companies are only protected by the government, rather than bought.
In order to meet everyone in Congress, a provision has been added that if the government were to face losses over the next five years because of that program, it could impose new taxes in order to maintain its balance.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first sum of 250 billion to which may be added another 100 billion if the president deems it necessary.
The $350 billion payment is expected to be ratified by a further vote by Congress.
In exchange for his help, Washington will get shareholdings in protected businesses that will earn him dividends in case of profit and that he can resell when the waters have calmed down.
According to the plan, the federal government will have the opportunity to delay the foreclosure procedures related to real estate loans and to set limits on the remuneration and start-up allowances paid to the executives of the companies involved.
Starting today, the plan’s architects would like to put it to the vote of the House of Representatives, and the Senate vote on Wednesday.
Despite all the efforts, it is still not certain that their plan will be given free rein.
Yesterday there were several votes against the bill, both on the Republican and Democratic side.
“Obviously, Washington doesn’t hear you,” Republican House Finance Committee member Scott Garrett told voters.
“We have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But it doesn’t take advantage of taxpayers.
Leader of a small group in Congress dubbed “the caucus of skeptics,” Democratic Rep. Brad Sherman presents the situation differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
“Four hundred eminent professors of economics, including three Nobel laureates, have written to us to say: We ask Congress not to jump to conclusions and to carefully examine the way forward,” he said.
At the same time, Europe was once again witnessing the test of the global nature of the crisis.
After an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalization of the Fortis banking group for 11.2 billion euros ($16.3 billion).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg became necessary when the French bank BNS Paribas announced that it would abandon the purchase of its competitor, in full bankruptcy after the loss of 2 billion euros (2.9 billion dollars) for the crisis of at-risk real estate loans in the United States.
Fortis employs 85,000 people and is one of Europe’s twenty largest banks and ten largest insurers.
"It's not the money lost," Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said yesterday.
In return, influence and voting rights are levied on banking matters.
It is certainly something that savers and families appreciate now that the times are uncertain.”
During this period, at the other end of the Channel, the British government seems to be on the way to nationalizing another bank in the balance sheet for the financial crisis.
According to the British press, the government would take over all of the loans currently underway at Bradford and Bringley, of which more than 41 billion ($75.5 billion) of real estate loans.
Spanish bank Santander said it would buy the UK bank’s branches and customer accounts.
Since the beginning of the economic crisis, Bradford and Bringley will be the second bank, after Northern Rock, to undergo a process of nationalization by the British government.
