What was produced in the Zuschlag & Partners invoice factory?
Soon, on October 8, the hearing of the criminal trial against János Zuschlag and partners will be discussed.
The politician and his associates are accused of repeated commercial fraud committed as part of a criminal association that has caused considerable damage, and of other crimes, including forgery of documents.
According to the Prosecutor's Office, the money obtained from competition calls was used by them for private purposes, and they often certified the carrying out of the activities by means of fake invoices.
The state and municipal money, in total 65 million guldens, ended up in part in the coffers of the organization Fiatal Baloldal, in part in the pockets of some people.
According to the method, reported by the investigating authorities, they have withdrawn the money obtained from competition notices on the basis of invoices for non-existent transactions and the associations have never fulfilled their obligations.
According to the indictment, most of the invoices were false.
To make them, the blocks of invoices were purchased at the Józsefváros market, the circular stamps instead were manufactured in Kiskunhalas.
And to decide on behalf of which companies to issue the invoices, it was established among other things during the trip through the hills over the Balaton where János Zuschlag had sent István Lados.
According to his confession, he had to choose pensions and restaurants.
He asked for an invoice for the consumptions, modelled after these were then prepared the invoices to be forwarded to the competition calls, among others, to those of the Ministry for Youth and Sport, the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs and the City of Budapest.
A large part of these are the work of István Lados and András ?ri, who, according to our information, has drawn up mainly the reports necessary to obtain funding.
One of the choices of Lados' "journey studies" was a brewery.
According to two invoices issued by Zuschlag and partners in 2003, the restaurant provided meals for a group of 90 people of the Biztos Pont Egyesület Association.
So many people, however, according to the restaurant owner, would not all enter the restaurant together.
Similarly, the invoice issued in the summer of 2002 to the Jobb Jövèrt Foundation, later named Együtt in Harmadik Évezredért, is full of formal and content errors.
A guesthouse in Badacsonytomaj has only three rooms, more than 10 people could not stay there, however there were 130 guests on the invoice.
But the compilers of the fancy-filled invoices exaggerated when they reported to Pigal Kft., which also deals with catering, whose accounting - according to information issued to the judicial authorities - did not even include the documents on behalf of Jobb Jövért and Hoppá companies.
The company’s director, Gyoz Farkas, told hvg.hu that when he was summoned to the prosecutor’s office and the invoices were shown to him, he immediately realized that they were fake documents.
"On the stamp the name and the VAT match of our company were at the wrong place."
He added: in addition to the formal reasons, there was also the fact that according to the invoice one hundred people were accommodated, when in total they have eleven rooms and there are not so many beds.
On the other hand, the invoice was for catering and their restaurant has not been in operation for some time.
Frequent invoice compilers did not bother to learn that the Budapest travel agency of their choice only organizes trips abroad, so they foolishly indicated on the invoice with cash payment trips to Hungary, which did not agree with the practice of issuing invoices of the company.
In addition, as demonstrated during the investigation, VAT was also included on the invoice, while the activity of travel to countries outside the European Union is exempt from VAT.
Among other things, the amount of the VAT was also incorrect on the four documents issued by the Hotel Révfülöp Kft. in favor of the Jobb Jövèrt Foundation, in fact, on the services offered by the company it is necessary to apply the VAT at 15% and not 25% as indicated on the invoices, in addition the hotel employees issued only printed invoices, while the invoice was written by hand.
In addition to this, the "issuers" ruined other invoices, in the case of a company they indicated as activity carried out the transport of goods by road, as is known from the prosecution procedure, activity that was not carried out by the company originally founded for investment advice.
Also for formal defects - non-conforming invoice size cause, fake stamp - it was found that invoices issued in favor of Együtt to Harmadik Evezredért Alapítvány, of XXI. Századi Kulturális Egyesület and Biztos Pont are fake.
The same was the case for Ravenna Bt. or the Kunfehértó Sports Field, whose representatives denied that they had issued the invoices in question.
The counterfeiters did not even pay attention to the fact that the HIB Kft. of Nyíregyháza was in liquidation when (2001) there lunched a group of Fiatal Városért Egyesület, precisely for this reason the curator of the liquidation of the firm, according to our information, denied that he issued that invoice.
They issue invoices knowingly.
Another group of invoice issuers consists of those who were aware of having to issue fictitious invoices.
The Esély Budapestért Alapítvány Foundation issued an invoice at the request of Fiatal Baloldal - Ifjú Szocialisták in favour of the Együtt Foundation in Harmadik Évezredért of almost 4 million gulden.
Ludovic Györfi, one of the defendants, according to the indictment, persuaded the director of the Collab Kft. to issue fictitious invoices.
He collaborated with Zuschlag and partners also with Biogate Kft, currently in liquidation, which in 2003 provided invoices worth about 5 million gulden to the Jobb Jöv?ert Alapítvány Foundation, the Atlasz Egyesület Association and the Vörösfeny Egyesület Association, behind which there was no real economic activity.
No movement of money because the prepared invoices were then reversed, but the associations forgot to include this aspect in their documents.
In the following group of companies issuing invoices belong those who are connectable with the defendants.
For example, Ivan Kubatov, authorized to contact the general manager of the Delta Trió Kft, based in Budapest but not available there, who deals in fuel and motor vehicles.
The company issued several invoices in October, November and December 2005 related to the sale of computer equipment, worth about 18 million gulden.
According to the data of the investigation, Cash Investment Kft. of Kiskunhalas under liquidation since 14 September 2005 purchased these invoices.
The director-general of this firm was a Romanian to whom Ivan Kubatov would forward documents concerning the firm between 2002 and 2005.
As far as we know, Kubatov, during the investigation, acknowledged that he had issued invoices on behalf of the company to the companies Atlasz, Hoppá and Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány and the countervalue was taken from him.
At the express request of Ivan Kubatov, Romanian bricklayers founded the companies Fa-Bani Jos Faipari Kft. and Jos-Investment Bt.
However, none of the companies were operational because the defendant said they had not received a job.
However, the companies were useful because, at the request of the co-deputy lawyer Zsolt Szente, the editor of the company's founding documents, invoices were issued on behalf of the companies to the associations linked to Zuschlag: the Atlasz and the Y-Generación.
On behalf of Cash Investment, Delta Trió, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade Kubatov issued 15 invoices worth 14.2 million gulden.
The prosecutor's office believes that Kubatov pocketed 10% of the amounts shown on the invoices, as well as VAT.
The man also used the Szi-Beri Bt. to issue fictitious invoices, manufactured for the Biztos Pont competition call.
Y-Generáció and Szövetség at Modern Magyarországért in January 2006 submitted a tender for the Socialist Party's public utility, Táncsics Mihály Alapítvány (TMA).
They also won 500,000 guldens per head but the sums were not used for the purposes indicated in the call.
In order for this not to come to light, they presented TMA with five fictitious invoices received from the Works Team Kft.
These invoices were found during the search of the office of Árpád Kemecsei at the Ministry of Education.
At the hearing a part of the defendants, as they have already done in the prosecutor's office, will probably report on the development of the production of the invoices.
However, the most interesting thing could be if the number one defendant, János Zuschlag, decided to lift the veil on everything.
His confession has so far not been very detailed and although he has repeatedly promised to talk about everything extensively, he has not yet done so.
We must see if it is in his interest, it could also be that the Socialists have made agreements with Zusi, who - in exchange for compensation of 50 million gulden, much of the damage - would be willing to make the scapegoat.
Zuschlag for now could also have been offended as his demands to lighten his conditions of imprisonment, namely the granting of house arrests, have so far not been met.
While the perpetrators of non-compensable commercial crimes and causing much greater harm can freely walk around or at least wait at home for the end of the proceedings against them, which is not granted to him.
The Psychology of Excess Bidding: Why Spend More Money?
At auctions, buyers are likely to spend more, overestimate the goods.
Neurologists and economists at the University of New York have managed to uncover the neuro-economic underpinnings of this well-known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to their study published in the journal Science, men do not want to be left behind in a race such as the eBay auction, so they are available to pay even a higher price.
The research sought to trace the nervous pattern of this "match" at the level of the nervous system through experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played the lot, the other group of players participated in an auction while using the functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) method they examined the active areas of the brains of the people participating in the experiment.
In both games participants could win money, but in the auction game, where the substantial element is to bid more than the other, the striated body under the cerebral cortex comes into operation intensively when you lose to the game.
This brain area, in addition to other functions, plays a role in the "self-gratification" mechanism of the nervous system.
Therefore, according to the researchers, the price increase is explained by scanning the vehement reaction of the striated body.
To support their theory, the economists of the research group conducted a financial tracking survey.
In this survey three groups bid against a partner under different conditions.
The control group was told how much the actual value of the product in question was and they made their bet.
Another group has promised that in case of winning they will receive another prize of $15.
The third group would receive $15 before the auction, but the members of the group would lose money in the event of a loss at the auction.
The difference between the two groups was that for one of them the win was stressed, while for the other the loss.
Proving the neurologists’ hypothesis, members of the group who played “against the loss” were willing to make higher bets than the control or “winning” group.
“These results are not deductible from any of the previously existing economic theories.
These thus far explained the phenomena encountered at auctions with the joy of winning and avoiding risk.
Only methods of creating the neurological image have helped solve the contradiction between the two theories, so that we have come to a third explanation,” said Andrew Schotter, a professor in the Faculty of Economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: when to go to the doctor?
Nearly half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while chronic liver disease is one of the leading causes of death in Hungary.
In Hungary the number of hepatitis sufferers amounts to one hundred thousand, of these only 7,000 are treated: the reason is that many patients do not know they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective name of contagious liver diseases caused by several viruses.
There are many similarities between the symptoms, typical are hepatitis and jaundice, but their pathogens and diseases caused differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses spread in two main forms depending on the pathogen: hepatitis A and E via the food channel (e.g., water and infected foods), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and organic fluids (sperm, vaginal discharge, saliva).
For those who travel it is useful to get vaccinated against the virus A and B, against C there is no vaccine.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after eating infected foods, accompanied by general malaise, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After yellowish spots form on the skin and white of the eyes, feces become light and dark urine, healing takes place within two to three weeks.
One million people die each year worldwide from hepatitis B, the most serious variant of the disease, which causes liver cancers and liver cirrhosis.
The main reason is, according to estimates, that only one in ten people receives pharmacological treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if it is not treated it can cause liver cirrhosis and liver cancers.
Most infected people do not know that they have contracted the disease because pathogens subtly destroy liver cells, in many cases the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
Therefore, it is very important to prevent and perform regular medical tests.
This disease is much more common than the average in three groups: those who had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts and tattoos.
Worldwide, the number of people infected with the chronic hepatitis C virus is 200 million.
Since even a routine laboratory examination reveals the disease it is worthwhile to consult your family doctor when you notice any symptoms of unknown origin.
Recognized in time the disease is curable, the virus can be eliminated from the body, so the infectious power ceases and the formation of tumors can be prevented.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, organized for the first time in 2004 by patient associations around the world.
The aim is to draw attention to chronic viral hepatitis, the causes of its development and the early recognition of the disease.
Does anyone who believes in God feel less pain?
According to a recent survey, religious faith functions as a kind of analgesic that has made the death of Catholic martyrs more bearable.
Scientists at the University of Oxford have performed an interesting experiment, examining how faith in god affects the sensation of pain, the British Telegraph reported.
As part of the somewhat bizarre investigation, an electroshock was carried out on 12 Catholic believers and atheists, while all were observing a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to repel much of the pain.
Thanks to the exploration technique of the human brain, it was discovered that Catholics were able to activate the part of the brain responsible for controlling pain.
The test is the first in a series of researches in which scientists, philosophers and theologians of the University take part in addition to academics.
The test was done exactly this way: an instrument that emits discharges and passes the electroshock was connected to the left hand of the subject of the experiment.
The researchers asked participants to focus on two paintings, the Virgin Mary painted in the seventeenth century by Sassoferrato and the Lady with Leonardo da Vinci's hermitage painted in the fifteenth century.
The authors of the examination hoped that the image of the Virgin Mary would give rise to a kind of religious state among believers, while Leonardo's painting was chosen because it did not differ too much from the other and they considered it to have a tranquilizing effect.
The subjects of the experiment spent half an hour in front of the MRI scanner and during this time they received 20 electroshocks in four consecutive series, while observing either the religious-themed painting or the other.
Catholics reported that the vision of the Virgin Mary made them feel “safe,” as if “someone cared for them” and “were reassured and were filled with peace.”
Looking at the religious-themed image, they accounted for 12% less pain than when Leonardo’s work was before them.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who took part in the test himself, believes that such a result can be achieved with any image with a strong effect even for atheists, but we must find the right image.
“We have to look for an image that they have very positive feelings toward, like a mother or father,” he said.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright was pleased with the result of the research.
“The practice of faith should change, and in many cases it can change our personality,” Wright added.
After the excellent results, only the question remains whether the painting of a Madonna by Leonardo or another painter of this caliber is presented to believers, what effect could it have on pain control?
Would the vision of a quality Virgin Mary bring better results?
You are what you say about yourself
On their 10th birthday, Google can claim to be as much in people’s pockets as in the sky above their heads; they know where they spent their holidays, what clinic they attend and what interests them.
This, however, according to Eric Schmidt, one of the directors of the company, is still not enough.
What concerns skeptics who make a comparison with the Orwellian nightmare, they do not see the very substance of web 2.0.
Eric Schmidt recently told the Financial Times that Google’s main purpose is to collect as much personal data as possible from its users, and this is necessary to meet the original goal of Google’s founders: “Let’s put all the information in the world into one system!”
According to the director of Google interviewed the company, after 10 years of revolutionary work, it is still at the beginning of being able to manage all the information.
When asked what will happen in five years, Schmidt replied: he would like to know if Google could answer questions like “what do I do tomorrow?” or “what’s the right job for me?” but software doesn’t know how to answer seemingly simple questions because they don’t know enough about users.
Not all Internet users are aware that during their search on the internet are recorded exactly the words searched, from which IP address they are searched and on which page the interested parties stop after the search.
Through the Personalized Search launched two years ago users can e.g. memorize their browsing history, they can relate to what they have searched and clicked, these will then in the long run generate much better tailor-made results; on this same logic is based Recommendations with which the system offers us products and services based on our previously declared and registered preferences.
What happens if my data is used against me, if they look at what I do? - Google data monopoly users wonder.
In most cases, the counter-reactions of Internet users are provoked by the fear of the size of the potential power represented by the company, and not by guilt, fear of punishment, desire for freedom or even rebellion against power.
One fact is confirmed, however, that all searched expressions are not only recorded but in justified cases can also be provided to third parties, in such legal cases nothing defends the personal rights of Internet users.
The most striking example of this in recent times has been perhaps the coordinated action against paedophiles in Brazil, in which Google forwarded to the Brazilian government the information that made it possible to identify paedophiles from the Orkut community page maintained by Google.
Internet users worried about personal rights sighed for relief in May when the firm - in agreement with the electronic legal protection association EFF - successfully proved the truth in court against the FBI: even then Google cannot be forced with any point of the constitution to provide any information secretly requested by the FBI.
(At the same time, the federal government successfully ripped out nearly 50,000 web addresses and a thousand search expressions obtained in reference to the confirmation of the child protection law passed years earlier, but still failed to obtain individual users’ search lists and the entire list of web pages and keywords dating back two months.)
Google’s judgment is therefore quite contradictory: those who fear providing their personal data beat up Google because they believe that this is how their intimate sphere and private life is affected by starting to use its services and rise up with the rebellion of the multinationals that stand out for the conservative image.
Meanwhile, the American geek culture and the proliferation of enthusiasts, activists and computer users who have appeared in many countries see in them the next generation of big companies, the "cool corporation", unlike their rival, Microsoft liquidated as the conqueror of the world because of Windows, although both fight for the same goal.
This can happen because Google, unlike Microsoft, does not ask its users for an identification code, does not ask for money for its services, the source code kept always up to date and the program package is much more accessible, youthful and cool than the official practice of the software giant.
But it can also happen because geeks see exactly the problematic relationship between personal rights and the internet, which implies just one of the most frequently repeated keywords in recent years, the web 2.0.
Web 2.0 is all about collaboration, intentionally leaving traces behind us and exploiting the communication channels at our disposal and while the size of these changes for each individual, the substance is the same: to show ourselves.
An average young person can create profiles on multiple community pages, from Facebook to Shanghai, can connect them with other services such as Twitter or last.fm that list their musical tastes, all of these can insert them in systems such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm, can also write blogs on which his most recent photo galleries automatically appear on Flickr or Picasa.
Meanwhile, we read of numerous exemplary cases from which it is clear that the girl, seeing the series of photos taken in the morning by the common tour of friends, comes to know easily who spent the night with her treacherous boyfriend or a company can fire its employee because he wrote a sincere opinion on the company summit: one thing is certain, the concept of private life has now completely reconsidered.
Those who live a life online make sure to show themselves and so we can formulate the fundamental thesis that hides behind the behavior of young people.
Those who want to hide something or just avoid the monopoly of Google can do so (starting with Scroogle using the Google search system but which at the same time does not voluntarily leave traces).
There are not a few people who do not sign up on purpose to community pages to not be found, Google’s online applications, from word processing to image management and news collection, can be replaced with alternative versions not linked to huge server parks and that do not make up our best existing profile so far.
Public opinion doesn’t wait so long in secret when Google pulls its claws out.
