The intelligent machine mimics the flight of the hornet
What could be the best method to develop anti-collision technologies if not mimicking the sensors of obstacles found in nature?
For example, the bees.
In the astonishing project presented at CEATEC in Japan, the Hornets gave the initial strategic inspiration to Nissan engineers on how to build the next generation of anti-collision systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the BR23C biomimetic robot, a robotic mini-car with bee properties, with the ultimate goal of creating a system that can scan all collisions.
Flying bees form their own personal oval space that really looks a lot like our protective shield - explained Kazuhiro Doi, director of PR technology and R&D.
Important is the role of the sight of the bee, capable of a visual of 300 degrees in each direction.
The engineers took advantage of the telemetric laser idea to copy the function of the bee’s view.
The BR23C detects obstacles up to two meters away within a radius of 180 degrees, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the onboard microprocessor that immediately turns it into a command to avoid collision.
In a fraction of a second the robot perceives the obstacle and then, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes direction by turning the wheels of the necessary measure to avoid the accident.
This avoidance manoeuvre, unlike the current system, takes place entirely instinctively.
“If it weren’t, the robot car wouldn’t react quickly to avoid collisions,” explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Lab and the robot car project.
It must react instinctively and immediately because this technology corresponds to the damaged and innermost layer of the protective shield, within which the collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what a bee does to avoid the other bees.
This process must take place in the blink of an eye.
But unlike bees, the deviation cannot go up or down or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and in the direction of steering of the wheels.
In this way, instead of the endless possibilities available to the bees to scan the other bees, the robot, as a possibility available, can rotate on itself, accelerate and slow down.
The BR23C is powered by lighter, high energy density lithium polymer batteries, which means that their lifespan is longer than that of lithium ions.
Andoh says it’s important to have the instantaneous intelligent reaction, not the processing of data or even less the ability to store it.
This robot has to process some inputs in seconds and react.
There is no need to store and react with intuitive logic based on previous maneuvering data, so it only uses a memory of a few tens of Kb.
There is no need for a gigabyte or megabyte memory.
This is the first step towards the development of a technology for the immediate avoidance of collisions that, according to Nissan, can be installed in 10 years on the series vehicles.
Another possibility of application can be represented by the unification with the GPS satellite navigation system that avoiding the obstacles present on the road leads to the destination.
