"Most young Roma do not have a middle-level degree and as a result of low-quality elementary education only a small number of them can achieve a higher degree."
Járóka also stressed, as a fundamental human right, the key role of education in enforcing human rights.
Investing in the education of Roma children can mean strengthening the economy of the member states of the European Union.
She believes that it is necessary to raise awareness among Roma and non-Roma in the wider context of these connections.
In fact, the sooner a Roma starts school, the greater their chances of becoming a productive member of the labor market; through taxes paid for income and consumption they contribute to the nation’s budget.
“The right of European citizenship of the Roma must guarantee their right to quality education and the elimination of low-level and segregated schools,” said Lívia Járóka.
According to the MEP, the union of purpose and action of the European Union is necessary to accelerate the processes of desegregation of schools and for this reason it is of fundamental importance that the existing and planned anti-discrimination directives are properly respected.
"The vicious cycle of poverty, segregation and unemployment must be interrupted, we must give Roma children the opportunities granted by the democratic space so that they can contribute as full citizens of the future of Europe," she asked.
In the spirit of the "European Year of Equal Opportunities" to be guaranteed for all, the aim of the European Summit on Equal Opportunities organized every year since last year's Berlin meeting is to ensure a single forum to promote the objectives of anti-discrimination and equal opportunities set at state and European level.
