Mp3 players indicted, endangering hearing
Listening to loud music for an extended period of time using portable music devices such as MP3 players can cause permanent hearing injuries.
This is what the European Commission reports, which in a statement released in Brussels cites the opinion of the EU Scientific Committee on Emerging and Newly Identified Health Risks (CSRSERI), published today.
"From this scientific opinion, it emerges that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to music with portable music devices weekly for more than an hour a day holding the device at high volume risk a permanent loss of hearing ability."
“I’m concerned that such a large number of young people who frequently use portable music devices and high-noise mobile phones can unconsciously damage their hearing irreparably,” Kuneva says.
“From the scientific findings, a clear risk emerges and we need to react quickly.
What matters most is that we need to raise consumer awareness and make this information public.
We must also re-examine the existing control systems, in the light of this scientific opinion, to ensure that they are fully effective and keep pace with the new technology.”
Brussels had asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the large use of portable music devices and the increase in the number of young people exposed to the noise they caused.
"Scientists confirm that there is cause for concern and the European Commission will now examine together with Member States and stakeholders what steps could be taken to better protect children and adolescents from exposure to noise from portable music devices and related equipment."
Currently, there is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable music equipment to 100 dB, but there are growing concerns about the hearing damage that can result from excessive exposure to such sources of noise.
You can greatly limit this damage by resorting to solutions such as reducing levels and duration of exposure to noise.
In its opinion, the EU Scientific Committee notes that users of portable music equipment if they listen to loud music (more than 89 decibels) for only 5 hours per week exceed the limits currently in force for the maximum noise allowed in the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for longer periods risk a permanent loss of hearing ability after a period of 5 years.
This would affect 5-10% of users of such devices and their number can be quantified between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
