Elites in Danger
The phenomenon had already manifested itself a few days ago with the House vote against the $700 billion bailout plan launched by the White House: a significant portion of Americans were, and are, more interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the economy.
Yesterday’s New York Times confirmed this by informing us that the ongoing crisis is breaking up the Republican Party, increasingly divided between its old, moderate East Coast soul, favorable to federal institutions and the business community, and its new, conservative soul, hostile to “those of Washington” and the world of finance, strong especially in the Central and Southern states.
The soul, by the way, which became arrogantly alive with the vow I was saying at the beginning.
But this just mentioned is only one example of the changes, of the great changes, which the current economic earthquake may foretell or already reveal: not only in the United States but throughout the West and perhaps not here alone.
Both in the US and in Europe, the crisis seems to act as an accelerator of long-incubated phenomena that in the new climate solidify and finally come to light.
The first of these phenomena is the re-actualization, the extraordinary revival, of the dual state-sovereignty category in relation to a sort of renationalization of the economy.
The crisis, in fact, is a crisis of banking-financial institutions that, yes, have close links with abroad, but that first of all involve the budgets of people and families living in a single country, in a single state.
This immediately creates a political problem for those who govern it: that is, how to respond to the difficulties and protests of those people and families who, among other things, are also an electorate.
In short, the crisis appears economically global but politically it is almost exclusively national.
Political internationalism seems basically out of the question or does not have much to say: the clear proof is given by the European Union which is divided as usual between the different interests and between the different state strategies fails to decide any common political line.
And so it is from the government of every single state that everyone expects interventions, rescue and relaunch plans, new rules, and above all the provision of funds: since when it comes to tightness it is only the states that have the economic resources, the mass of financial resources that can try to put things right.
And they also possess the necessary means and the legitimacy to use them: two resources of immeasurable value, in certain circumstances, which no market or international organization can possibly ever have in a similar measure.
This new emphasis that the crisis places on the state-national element is, moreover, in perfect harmony with the ever-increasing importance that more recent developments in the economy tend to attach to a factor very closely linked to that element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, while we were convinced that we had entered the realm of the web, of increasingly sophisticated technology, of the immaterial, while we were convinced that globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we suddenly realized that our future will instead have to deal increasingly with those very immaterial things that are water, crops, oil.
All things that, look at it, can certainly be transported from one place to another on earth but are still absolutely linked to a limited space, to a territory.
So those who find themselves to be sovereign, certainly possess several more cards than those who are not, to those who have the misfortune to live in a place without crops, without oil and without water.
I come to the second novelty, which, however, presages a fracture.
Whoever says Territory, State, Government inevitably says Politics, and therefore Leadership.
In this regard, the economic crisis seems to produce two convergent phenomena.
On the one hand, the awareness of the objective need for authoritative leadership, the request of someone who knows how to take the situation in hand.
On the other hand, a wave of discredit for existing leaders, especially economic ones, proved so inadequate and full of shadows.
And together, something even deeper and in a certain sense disturbing: a discredit, a disgust, an image of inadequacy, a sense of distance, which tends to involve the entire ruling class in a growing number of Western countries.
That is to say, there seems to be a growing belief in broad sectors of the population that before their actions are the same as the ideas of the social elites up until now, their way of feeling and being, their culture in the overall sense of the term, to have made their own time and to be increasingly alien to the opinions of the majority.
The demand for leadership, in short, feeds underground a branched but powerful movement of delegitimization of the ruling classes and the traditional political arrangements, which manifests itself in the sudden electoral "revolts" or in the sudden turns of the collective moods of these last and last, from the conservative rise in Austria-Bavaria to the collapse of the American consensuses.
One has the impression that the traditional elites, their parties, their programs, but also their rites, their newspapers, their accredited intellectuals, their formats, some would say, make it increasingly difficult to understand, and therefore to represent, what is not taking shape from today in the deep layers of Western societies and that the economic crisis invigorates, increases, potentially agitates.
In the face of all this, talking about a “rebellion of the masses” on the agenda would be frankly exaggerated.
But keeping your eyes open is certainly not for nothing.
The superglue to walk on the walls
Defeat the laws of gravity thanks to a super glue and in the future walk on walls like Spiderman.
It is the target of several American research centers and now a team of four institutions has come very close to it.
With a sticker of just 2.5 square centimetres, the researchers managed to glue a body of 100 kilograms on a vertical wall.
The American journal Science has published the findings of researchers from the University of Dayton, Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
