“The glue principle can be imagined as a series of tubes arranged like a spaghetti pile,” explains Zhong Lin Wang of the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
The scientists were inspired by the legs of the geckos, covered with microscopic hairs that manage to ensure a perfect adhesion to the animal.
Tests conducted on different materials, such as glass, Teflon and glazed paper, have shown that the new adhesive is ten times more powerful than the legs of these reptiles and at the same time “is easily detached from the wall,” explains Liming Dai, a research fellow at the University of Dayton’s Faculty of Engineering.
"This material could be useful as a transient adhesive," adds Liming Dai.
Maybe to walk on walls just like Spiderman? Maybe so, but researchers think of a much less fascinating use as the connection between electronic devices, because carbon nanotubes are conductors of heat and electric current.
Other applications could involve aerospace engineering.
No superheroes at the moment.
