Goodbye old cinema Paradise, cities erase historic halls
The historic cinemas close in favor of the Multiplex.
“A city without cinemas is a blind city, it’s like a face without eyes.”
The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore effectively photographs what is happening in the major Italian urban centers but also in the cities of the province.
The process of marginalization of cinemas, with the birth on the outskirts of the large multisales and the consequent death by consumption of monosales in the central areas of the cities, is one of those events that seem inescapable and incontrovertible but also has all the characteristics of a real cultural crime.
Disappearing are often historical and memory-filled places, "it's as if a friend, an acquaintance with whom we shared a piece of the road and so many emotions," observes the director of Nuovo Cinema Paradiso, the film that twenty years ago won Tornator the Oscar and the Grand Prix of the Cannes jury, and that told the poetry of a provincial hall and the nostalgia for a way of living perhaps the cinema.
The figures provided by the Anec, the main association of retailers, speak clearly: in the last five years, 316 traditional cinemas have closed, and the most important are the cinemas in the main cities: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closures is Emilia-Romagna with 82 single-room cinemas lost, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
And to demonstrate that the first responsible for their disappearance is the advent of the multiplex, it is precisely these three Italian regions that have recorded the most new multi-room cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in both Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
“The Italian exercise has developed irrationally,” notes Paolo Protti, president of the Anec, “it is useful that new structures are built but the survival of those already existing should be ensured, because when a city hall closes, not all its attendants are willing to move into multiplexes.
Not to mention the lack of funding for the fund in favor of traders: the state’s previous debt is about 10 million euros.
It is shameful, ethically and morally, that the government does not respect existing laws.
To support the sector would need between 16 and 18 million euros per year.”
Interesting is the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that, worried about the closures, decided to run for shelter with the signing of a protocol between the Municipality and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy, to protect and promote single-room cinemas both in the historic center and on the outskirts.
Among the rules provided for are tax relief measures in favour of managers and benefits for the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the restricted traffic area and will have special rates for parking and some parking lots.
“It’s an initiative that I like,” notes Giuseppe Tornatore, “and I hope other cities will follow Bologna’s example by setting up other measures.
It is certain, however, that to counteract the overpowering of multiplexes traditional rooms must also improve the quality of sound and image, because the public today is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that has always been important to me: the closure of the Supercinema di Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to do "Nuovo Cinema Paradiso", which I had been thinking about for 10 years.
