When the energy is born from the waves, the big ones are now on the field.
It’s an exterminated field, occupying over 70% of the planet’s surface and now the world’s major energy companies are discovering it.
Waves, currents, tides are the new renewable sources on which they have put their eyes, and now they try to get their hands, giants like Chevron.
The possibility of obtaining energy from the movements of the sea has been studied for a hundred years now and in the 1970s, in conjunction with the first oil crisis, the researches intensified.
When the price of oil fell, around 1980, the idea of harnessing marine energy was put aside, but now environmental demands and the new rise in oil give the industry momentum.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimated in 2007 that 15 percent of the world’s electricity needs could be met by offshore wave power plants.
That would be twice the amount currently produced by nuclear power plants.
