The first company to bet on marine energy was Enersis, which in 2005 signed an agreement to build a plant in northern Portugal.
When the deal was announced, it seemed like a revolutionary step.
Two years later to bet on marine energy are more and more and among these companies always devoted to traditional energy.
“Chevron is studying ocean energy technologies,” a spokeswoman for a U.S.-based oil giant told the Wall Street Journal, “and is considering cooperating with us.”
The cooperation in question is about obtaining a permit from the U.S. Energy Commission, which is needed to start a marine energy exploitation project in Alaska.
This is a sign, especially considering that in Alaska the US continues to extract oil and recently President Bush has started a plan for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, New York’s Verdant Power Inc. and New Jersey’s Ocean Power are on the road to energy from the sea, and the amounts invested so far, though not known in detail, indicate rising interest.
Technology to be developed.
Experts talk about a technology still in its infancy, also because marine energy does not escape all doubts about the environmental impact.
For now, plants like the Portuguese one or some in Scotland are small and do not seem to create major problems for the ecosystem.
However, to produce energy on a large scale, we must use technologies with a greater environmental impact.
And the choices are different: the Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of connected buoys.
The thrust of the waves, which causes the buoys to move up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure by pistons and cylinders inside the floats.
The pressure turns a turbine which in turn powers a generator.
Electricity is sent to shore through submarine cables.
For now there are four plants of this type being designed, waiting only for federal approval and part of the energy could be used for a military installation.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, already produces power for a shopping mall and parking lot using six underwater turbines in New York’s East River.
The movement of water when there are tides spins the turbine blades, creating a rotating motion that powers a generator.
Verdant said it has a long list of customers waiting for the necessary authorizations to take advantage of the energy.
After the waves, the tides.
Of particular interest, say the Institute for Electricity Research, is currently deserving of the potential of the tides.
Although it is an intermittent phenomenon, the tide is more predictable than wind, sun or waves and therefore more reliable as a source of energy.
It is precisely on the energy of the tides that states such as New York, Maine and Alaska, along with others on the coast, have already invested $7.5 million in 2008 and planned investments up to $35 million by 2009.
